<p>Let me ask you something: <strong>do you know exactly how many booked jobs came from your ad spend last month?</strong></p>

<p>Not clicks. Not impressions. Not "website visitors." Booked jobs. Actual revenue. If you can't answer that question with a specific number, you're not advertising. You're gambling.</p>

<h2 id="the-agency-play">The Agency Play</h2>

<p>Here's how most ad agencies work with service businesses:</p>

<p>They set up some Google Ads. They pick some keywords. They write some ad copy. They send you a monthly report showing you got 847 impressions and 23 clicks and your cost-per-click is $12.47.</p>

<p>And you stare at it and think, "Is that good?" And they say, "That's great. Let's increase the budget."</p>

<p>But here's the question they never answer: <strong>how many of those 23 clicks turned into phone calls? How many of those phone calls turned into booked jobs? What was the actual return on what you spent?</strong></p>

<p>They don't answer because they don't know. Or worse — they do know, and the answer isn't pretty.</p>

<blockquote>
<p>"If your ad agency can't tell you your cost per booked job, they're not managing your ads. They're managing your expectations."</p>
</blockquote>

<h2 id="the-math">The Math That Matters</h2>

<p>Advertising for a service business comes down to one formula:</p>

<div class="callout">
    <p class="callout-title">💰 The Only Formula That Matters</p>
    <p><strong>Money Spent on Ads ÷ Jobs Booked from Ads = Cost Per Acquisition</strong><br />
    If you spent $2,000 and booked 4 jobs averaging $3,000 each, you made $12,000 from $2,000. That's a 6x return. That's advertising.<br /><br />
    If you spent $2,000 and you "think" you got some calls but you're not sure which ones came from ads? That's a bonfire.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="why-ads-fail">Why Ads Fail (It's Usually Not the Ads)</h2>

<p>Here's the dirty secret: most ad campaigns for service businesses fail not because the ads are bad, but because <strong>what happens after the click is broken.</strong></p>

<ul>
    <li>The landing page is your homepage (terrible)</li>
    <li>The phone number isn't click-to-call on mobile</li>
    <li>Nobody answers the phone during peak ad hours</li>
    <li>The form submission doesn't trigger an instant response</li>
    <li>There's no tracking to connect the click to the job</li>
</ul>

<p>You're paying to get people to your door, then leaving that door locked. The ads worked. Your system didn't.</p>

<h2 id="when-to-run-ads">When to Actually Run Ads</h2>

<p>This is the part agencies don't want to hear: <strong>not every business is ready for paid ads.</strong></p>

<p>If your website doesn't convert, ads will just send more people to a site that doesn't work. If you don't answer your phone, ads will generate calls you miss. If you can't track results, you'll never know if the ads are working.</p>

<p>Ads are Step 3 in the system. Not Step 1. Here's the order:</p>

<ol>
    <li><strong>Fix your website and follow-up system.</strong> Make sure when someone contacts you, the experience is seamless.</li>
    <li><strong>Build your organic presence.</strong> Google Business Profile, reviews, local SEO. Free traffic first.</li>
    <li><strong>Then turn on ads.</strong> Now you're sending paid traffic to a system that actually converts. Now the math works.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="red-flags">Red Flags Your Ad Agency Is Burning Your Money</h2>

<ul>
    <li>They report on impressions and clicks but never on booked jobs</li>
    <li>They want to increase your budget every month</li>
    <li>They can't explain where your money is going in plain English</li>
    <li>You don't have access to your own ad accounts</li>
    <li>They locked you into a long-term contract</li>
    <li>Your landing page is just your homepage</li>
</ul>

<p>If three or more of those apply, it might be time for a conversation. Not with them. With someone who'll tell you the truth.</p>

<p><strong>The goal isn't to spend more on ads. It's to make every dollar you spend traceable, accountable, and profitable.</strong></p>

